\subsection{Step 3 --- Insert the ILA core}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]

	\item \textbf{Open the IP Catalog.}
	In Vivado's Flow Navigator, click \textbf{IP Catalog} (under Project Manager). In the search box at the top of the catalog panel, type \texttt{ILA}. Double-click \textbf{ILA (Integrated Logic Analyzer)} to open the customization dialog.

	\item \textbf{Configure the core.}
	In the customization dialog:
	\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.5em]
		\item \textbf{General Options} tab: set \textbf{Number of Probes} to \texttt{12} and \textbf{Sample Data Depth} to \texttt{1024}.
		\item \textbf{Probe\_Ports} tab: a row appears for each probe (\texttt{PROBE0} through \texttt{PROBE11}). Set the \textbf{Probe Width} of each row to match the signal width from the table in Step~2 (e.g., \texttt{PROBE0} = 1 for \texttt{uart\_rxd\_sync}, \texttt{PROBE1} = 8 for \texttt{rx\_data}, and so on in table order).
		\item Click \textbf{OK}, then \textbf{Generate} when prompted to generate output products. Wait for the generation to complete before proceeding.
	\end{itemize}

	\item \textbf{Copy the instantiation template.}
	After generation, right-click the \texttt{ila\_0} entry that appears in the Sources panel under IP Sources and select \textbf{Open IP Example Design}, or navigate to \textbf{IP Sources $\to$ ila\_0 $\to$ Instantiation Template}. Open the \texttt{.vho} file and copy the component declaration and port map. You will paste this into \texttt{ingest\_top.vhd} in the next sub-step.

	\item \textbf{Declare the component in \texttt{ingest\_top.vhd}.}
	In the architecture declaration section (before \texttt{begin}), paste the component declaration from the template. It will look like:
	\begin{verbatim}
component ila_0 is
port (
    clk     : in std_logic;
    probe0  : in std_logic_vector(0  downto 0);
    probe1  : in std_logic_vector(7  downto 0);
    probe2  : in std_logic_vector(0  downto 0);
    -- ... probes 3-11 ...
    probe11 : in std_logic_vector(5  downto 0)
);
end component;
	\end{verbatim}

	\item \textbf{Connect the probe signals.}
	Inside the \texttt{gen\_debug} generate block from Step~1, paste the port map. Wire each probe port to the corresponding signal from the Step~2 table, in order:
	\begin{verbatim}
u_ila : ila_0
port map (
    clk     => CLK100MHZ,
    probe0  => (0 => uart_rxd_sync),
    probe1  => rx_data,
    probe2  => (0 => rx_valid),
    probe3  => (0 => rx_error),
    probe4  => parser_state,
    probe5  => byte_counter,
    probe6  => (0 => frame_valid),
    probe7  => (0 => frame_reject),
    probe8  => beacon_id,
    probe9  => pkt_type,
    probe10 => rssi_out,
    probe11 => fifo_count
);
	\end{verbatim}
	Note: single-bit signals must be wrapped as a 1-element vector, e.g.\ \texttt{(0 => uart\_rxd\_sync)}, because \mbox{ILA} probe ports are always \texttt{std\_logic\_vector}.

	\item \textbf{Verify the generate block boundary.}
	Confirm the \texttt{u\_ila} instantiation and nothing else is between \texttt{gen\_debug : if g\_DEBUG generate} and \texttt{end generate gen\_debug;}. All datapath logic (\texttt{u\_uart\_rx}, \texttt{u\_fifo}, \texttt{u\_parser}, etc.) must remain \emph{outside} the generate block.

\end{enumerate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[warning={\ILA{} Block RAM Cost}]
	This configuration (12 probes, 1024-sample depth) uses approximately 4 \BRAM{} tiles. The Module~2 pipeline uses 2 \BRAM{} tiles for the feature \BRAM{}. Total with the \ILA{}: 6 of 135 available \BRAM{} tiles on the Artix-7 100T. This is well within budget. The \ILA{} overhead is the primary reason to generate a separate production bitstream in LH3-E once debugging is complete.
\end{tcolorbox}

\subsection{Step 4 --- Re-synthesize and implement with debug}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item Confirm that \texttt{g\_DEBUG} is set to \texttt{true} in the top-level instantiation or testbench. In Vivado's \textbf{Sources} panel, right-click the top-level and set the generic value.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Run Synthesis}. Confirm zero errors. Warnings about \ILA{} probe widths being 1-bit are expected and harmless.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Run Implementation}. Confirm positive \mbox{WNS} --- the \ILA{} should not introduce timing violations on a 100\,MHz design of this size.
	\item Flow Navigator $\to$ \textbf{Generate Bitstream}. The output is \texttt{ingest\_top\_debug.bit}.
\end{enumerate}

\labfigure{LH3B_vivado_synthesis_ila.png}{0.85\textwidth}{Vivado synthesis report showing the \ILA{} core resource usage. The 4 \BRAM{} tiles for the capture buffer should be visible in the utilization section.}{fig:lh3b-synth}

\subsection{Step 5 --- Program the debug bitstream}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item Connect the Nexys A7 via USB. In Vivado Hardware Manager, program \texttt{ingest\_top\_debug.bit}.
	\item Vivado will prompt to associate the debug probes file (\texttt{.ltx}). Click \textbf{OK}.
	\item The \mbox{ILA} dashboard should open automatically. If it does not, go to \textbf{Tools $\to$ Open Debug Probes} and navigate to the generated \texttt{.ltx} file.
	\item Confirm that all 12 probe channels are visible and labeled.
\end{enumerate}

\labfigure{LH3B_ila_dashboard.png}{0.85\textwidth}{Vivado \ILA{} dashboard showing all 12 probe channels listed and idle (no \UART{} input connected yet). Confirm the channel names match the signal table before proceeding.}{fig:lh3b-ila-dashboard}

\subsection{Step 6 --- Baseline ILA verification (no STM32 connected)}
\begin{enumerate}[leftmargin=2em]
	\item With no signal connected to the \mbox{PMOD} \UART{} input pin, arm the \mbox{ILA} with a trigger on \texttt{rx\_valid} rising edge.
	\item Confirm that the trigger \emph{never} fires. If \texttt{rx\_valid} pulses with no input, the \mbox{PMOD} pin is floating and picking up noise. Pull the pin high with a 10\,k$\Omega$ resistor to \texttt{3V3} or add the pull-up in the \texttt{.xdc} constraint file:
	\begin{verbatim}
set_property PULLUP true [get_ports uart_rxd]
	\end{verbatim}
	\item Change the trigger to \texttt{frame\_valid} rising edge. Arm again. Confirm no spurious triggers.
	\item Set a basic trigger on \texttt{uart\_rxd\_sync} = \texttt{0} (falling edge). The dashboard should show \texttt{uart\_rxd\_sync} held at logic~1 (idle state for \UART{}).
\end{enumerate}

\begin{tcolorbox}[infobox={ILA Trigger Strategy for Integration Debugging}]
	Use different trigger signals at each debugging layer in LH3-C:
	\begin{itemize}[leftmargin=1.2em]
		\item \textbf{No byte activity?} Trigger on \texttt{uart\_rxd\_sync} falling edge (start bit). If it never fires, the physical layer is broken.
		\item \textbf{Bytes arrive but parser stalls?} Trigger on \texttt{rx\_valid} rising edge and watch \texttt{parser\_state}. If state stays in HUNT, the \texttt{0x7E} delimiter is missing.
		\item \textbf{Parser progresses but CRC rejects?} Trigger on \texttt{frame\_reject} rising edge and capture the full 43-byte \texttt{rx\_data} sequence for manual \CRC{} computation.
		\item \textbf{Integration success?} Trigger on \texttt{frame\_valid} rising edge and compare fields to the STM32 log.
	\end{itemize}
\end{tcolorbox}

